<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="151" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
Similarly to the melanic color form of 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. yukonensis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="yukonensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. yukonensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below), which was described as a distinct species, 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. scoticus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="scoticus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. scoticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cameron, P" journalOrPublisher="Ecological Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" refId="B26" refString="Cameron, P, 1881a. Description of a new species of Dolerus from Scotland. Entomologist's Monthly Magazine 17: 206." title="Description of a new species of Dolerus from Scotland. Entomologist's Monthly Magazine 17: 206." year="1881 a">Cameron (1881a)</bibRefCitation>
, the melanic form of 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. junci" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="junci">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. junci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was also described as a distinct species, 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. thargitai" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="thargitai">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. thargitai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by Zombori (regarded as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. yukonensis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="yukonensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. yukonensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. scoticus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="scoticus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. scoticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
until now). The melanic color form of 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. junci" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="junci">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. junci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has also been recorded from central Europe (Germany) and southern Europe (Italy, Switzerland: see, e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pesarini, F" journalOrPublisher="Annali del Museo civico di Storia naturale" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" pagination="69 - 83" refId="B146" refString="Pesarini, F, 2012. Nuovi reperti interessanti di Tentredinidi italiani (Hymenoptera, Symphyta, Tenthredinidae). Annali del Museo civico di Storia naturale 13 (2010): 69 - 83" title="Nuovi reperti interessanti di Tentredinidi italiani (Hymenoptera, Symphyta, Tenthredinidae)." volume="13" year="2012">Pesarini 2012</bibRefCitation>
), but is not known from Fennoscandia. The males of the melanic forms of 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. junci" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="junci">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. junci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(01.06.1984) and 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. yukonensis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="yukonensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. yukonensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(24.05.1984) have been collected at the same locality at nearly the same time (Germany: Federsee, Brackenhof, leg. E. Jansen, CEJ). In addition to their different penis valve structure and other characters used in the keys by 
<bibRefCitation author="Benson, RB" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" refId="B10" refString="Benson, RB, 1952. Hymenoptera, Symphyta. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 6(2b): 51-137." title="Hymenoptera, Symphyta. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 6 (2 b): 51 - 137." year="1952">Benson (1952)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhelochovtsev, AN" journalOrPublisher="Brill, Leiden" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" refId="B199" refString="Zhelochovtsev, AN, 1994. [Translation of the book published in Russian in 1988]. In: Medvedev GS (Ed.) Keys to the Insects of the European Part of the USSR. Volume III Hymenoptera Part VI Symphyta. E.J. Brill, Leiden" title="[Translation of the book published in Russian in 1988]. In: Medvedev GS (Ed.) Keys to the Insects of the European Part of the USSR. Volume III Hymenoptera Part VI Symphyta. E. J." year="1994">Zhelochovtsev (1994)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. junci" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="junci">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. junci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. yukonensis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="yukonensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. yukonensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ in the shape and sculpture of the mesoscutellar appendage: almost unsculptured and without a distinct longitudinal keel in the former, and clearly sculptured and with a distinct keel in the latter. Most likely, the melanic color form of 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. junci" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="junci">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. junci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not occur within the geographic range of 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. incisus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="incisus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. incisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but they can also be distinguished by the shape and the sculpture of the mesoscutellar appendage: meshed (nearly matt) and long, with a distinct median longitudinal keel (
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. incisus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="incisus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. incisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) versus short and almost unsculptured (more or less glossy) and without a distinct median keel (
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. junci" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="junci">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. junci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
